BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:CHE Seminar Series: Understanding the role of price caps in NDIS m
 arkets
DTSTART:20260401T120000
DTEND:20260401T130000
DESCRIPTION:This paper examines how providers in the National Disability I
 nsurance Scheme (NDIS) adjust prices and service volumes in response to pr
 ice cap changes. Using detailed service usage data from Kismet\, a plan ma
 nager for the NDIS\, we analyse short-run responses in the weeks following
  the 1 July 2025 price cap adjustments. Market prices respond quickly in b
 oth directions: a 1% increase in the cap raises provider prices by 0.61% o
 n average\, including providers that previously priced below the cap (“p
 ricing headroom”)\, while a 1% decrease lowers prices by 0.9%\, with lar
 ger reductions among providers previously at the cap. Service volumes rema
 in broadly stable\, with minor reductions concentrated among providers fac
 ing large cap cuts. These results highlight asymmetries in market response
 s and suggest that price cap adjustments affect both expenditure and servi
 ce provision\, underscoring the importance of ongoing monitoring of provid
 er behaviour.\n\nSpeaker profile\n\n<a href="https://spelinakyol.weebly.co
 m/" target="_blank">Pelin Akyol</a> is Research Manager at the e61 Institu
 te and an applied economist with a Ph.D. in Economics from Penn State Univ
 ersity. Her research focuses on education\, labour markets\, demographic c
 hange\, and health. Her recent work examines fertility decisions\, caregiv
 ing behaviour\, and gender differences in educational outcomes\, using sur
 vey and administrative data. Before joining e61\, she was an Assistant Pro
 fessor at Bilkent University. At e61\, she leads research on fertility and
  demographic challenges\, care responsibilities\, and the National Disabil
 ity Insurance Scheme.\n\nWeekly seminar series\n\nAs part of our Centre's 
 vibrant research culture\, we host a weekly seminar series. Visiting and i
 nvited researchers present current research relating to the economics of h
 ealth and wellbeing\, and the healthcare sector. Visitors are welcome to j
 oin these sessions where discussion and debate is encouraged.\n\nFor furth
 er information on our seminar series\, please contact <a href="mailto:Tro
 ng-Anh.Trinh@monash.edu">Trong-Anh.Trinh@monash.edu</a> .\n\n<a class="btn
 " href="https://monash.zoom.us/j/83600802355?pwd=1F4DXlfQDO7MHpjzEWsMC6dZb
 AX5do.1" target="_blank">Join Zoom</a>
LOCATION:Caulfield campus\, Building C\, level 1\, room C1.21
URL:https://www.monash.edu/business/events/che-seminar-series-understandin
 g-the-role-of-price-caps-in-ndis-markets
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:15th Australasian Workshop on Econometrics and Health Economics
DTSTART:20260415T123000
DTEND:20260417T123000
DESCRIPTION:This workshop will provide a forum for the development and dis
 semination of applications of econometrics and other quantitative approach
 es in health economics. It will follow the format of the long-running Euro
 pean workshops on econometrics and health economics.\n\nWe are now calling
  for papers for presentation\, with up to 14 papers to be accepted. Presen
 tations by doctoral students and early career researchers are encouraged.\
 n\nPapers accepted for presentation will each be allocated a 55-minute ses
 sion\, including 30 minutes for a presentation\, 10 minutes for an appoint
 ed discussant and 10 minutes for general discussion.\n\nThe number of work
 shop participants is strictly limited\, and participants will be expected 
 to attend the full workshop.\n\nPlease see the drop-down below for more in
 formation on papers\, including the submission deadline.\n\n<!-- false -->
 \n<div class="accordion nested-accordion js-frontend-complex-accordion" id
 ="Component-4158062" role="tablist">\n<div class="hidden">\n<span class="h
 idden nested-accordion__expand-text">View</span>\n<span class="hidden nest
 ed-accordion__collapse_text">Close</span>\n</div>\n<section class="panel s
 ection1 Paper_submissions-1 close">\n<h3 aria-controls="Paper_submissions-
